[src:random-walk-theory/first-hitting-time-model] In statistics, **first-hitting-time models** are simplified models that estimate the amount of time that passes before some random or stochastic process crosses a barrier, boundary or reaches a specified state, termed the **first hitting time**, or the **first passage time**.
[src:random-walk-theory/first-hitting-time-model] Accurate models give insight into the physical system under observation, and have been the topic of research in very diverse fields, from economics to ecology.
[src:random-walk-theory/first-hitting-time-model] The idea that a first hitting time of a stochastic process might describe the time to occurrence of an event has a long history, starting with an interest in the first passage time of Wiener diffusion processes in economics and then in physics in the early 1900s.
[src:random-walk-theory/first-hitting-time-model] Modeling the probability of financial ruin as a first passage time was an early application in the field of insurance.
[src:random-walk-theory/first-hitting-time-model] An interest in the mathematical properties of first-hitting-times and statistical models and methods for analysis of survival data appeared steadily between the middle and end of the 20th century.
[src:random-walk-theory/first-hitting-time-model] First-hitting-time models are a sub-class of survival models.
[src:random-walk-theory/first-hitting-time-model] A common example of a first-hitting-time model is a ruin problem, such as Gambler's ruin.
[src:random-walk-theory/first-hitting-time-model] In this example, an entity (often described as a gambler or an insurance company) has an amount of money which varies randomly with time, possibly with some drift.
[src:random-walk-theory/first-hitting-time-model] The model considers the event that the amount of money reaches 0, representing bankruptcy.
[src:random-walk-theory/first-hitting-time-model] The model can answer questions such as the probability that this occurs within finite time, or the mean time until which it occurs.
[src:random-walk-theory/first-hitting-time-model] First-hitting-time models can be applied to expected lifetimes, of patients or mechanical devices.
[src:random-walk-theory/first-hitting-time-model] When the process reaches an adverse threshold state for the first time, the patient dies, or the device breaks down.
[src:random-walk-theory/first-hitting-time-model] The time for a particle to escape through a narrow opening in a confined space is termed the narrow escape problem, and is commonly studied in biophysics and cellular biology.
[src:random-walk-theory/first-hitting-time-model] One of the simplest and omnipresent stochastic systems is that of the Brownian particle in one dimension.
[src:random-walk-theory/first-hitting-time-model] This system describes the motion of a particle which moves stochastically in one dimensional space, with equal probability of moving to the left or to the right.
[src:random-walk-theory/first-hitting-time-model] Given that Brownian motion is used often as a tool to understand more complex phenomena, it is important to understand the probability of a first passage time of the Brownian particle of reaching some position distant from its start location.
[src:random-walk-theory/first-hitting-time-model] This is done through the following means.
[src:random-walk-theory/first-hitting-time-model] The probability density function (PDF) for a particle in one dimension is found by solving the one-dimensional diffusion equation.
[src:random-walk-theory/first-hitting-time-model] (This equation states that the position probability density diffuses outward over time.
[src:random-walk-theory/first-hitting-time-model] It is analogous to say, cream in a cup of coffee if the cream was all contained within some small location initially.
[src:random-walk-theory/first-hitting-time-model] given the initial condition $p(x,t={0}\mid x_{0})=\delta (x-x_{0})$ ; where $x(t)$ is the position of the particle at some given time, $x_{0}$ is the tagged particle's initial position, and D is the diffusion constant with the S.I. units $m^{2}s^{-1}$ (an indirect measure of the particle's speed).
[src:random-walk-theory/first-hitting-time-model] The bar in the argument of the instantaneous probability refers to the conditional probability.
[src:random-walk-theory/first-hitting-time-model] The diffusion equation states that the rate of change over time in the probability of finding the particle at $x(t)$ position depends on the deceleration over distance of such probability at that position.
[src:random-walk-theory/first-hitting-time-model] This states that the probability of finding the particle at $x(t)$ is Gaussian, and the width of the Gaussian is time dependent.
[src:random-walk-theory/first-hitting-time-model] where the average is taken over all space (or any applicable variable).
[src:random-walk-theory/first-hitting-time-model] The *First Passage Time Density* (FPTD) is the probability that a particle has *first* reached a point $x_{c}$ at exactly time t (not at some time during the interval up to t ).
[src:random-walk-theory/first-hitting-time-model] This probability density is calculable from the *Survival probability* (a more common probability measure in statistics).
[src:random-walk-theory/first-hitting-time-model] Consider the absorbing boundary condition $p(x_{c},t)=0$ (The subscript c for the absorption point $x_{c}$ is an abbreviation for *cliff* used in many texts as an analogy to an absorption point).
[src:random-walk-theory/first-hitting-time-model] where $\operatorname {erf}$ is the error function.
[src:random-walk-theory/first-hitting-time-model] The relation between the Survival probability and the FPTD is as follows: the probability that a particle has reached the absorption point between times t and $t+dt$ is $f(t)\,dt=S(t)-S(t+dt)$ .
[src:random-walk-theory/first-hitting-time-model] The first-passage time for a Brownian particle therefore follows a Lévy distribution.
[src:random-walk-theory/first-hitting-time-model] This equation states that the probability for a Brownian particle achieving a first passage at some long time (defined in the paragraph above) becomes increasingly small, but is always *finite*.
[src:random-walk-theory/first-hitting-time-model] First hitting times are central features of many families of stochastic processes, including Poisson processes, Wiener processes, gamma processes, and Markov chains, to name but a few.
[src:random-walk-theory/first-hitting-time-model] The state of the stochastic process may represent, for example, the strength of a physical system, the health of an individual, or the financial condition of a business firm.
[src:random-walk-theory/first-hitting-time-model] The system, individual or firm fails or experiences some other critical endpoint when the process reaches a threshold state for the first time.
[src:random-walk-theory/first-hitting-time-model] The critical event may be an adverse event (such as equipment failure, congested heart failure, or lung cancer) or a positive event (such as recovery from illness, discharge from hospital stay, child birth, or return to work after traumatic injury).
[src:random-walk-theory/first-hitting-time-model] The lapse of time until that critical event occurs is usually interpreted generically as a ‘survival time’.
[src:random-walk-theory/first-hitting-time-model] In some applications, the threshold is a set of multiple states so one considers competing first hitting times for reaching the first threshold in the set, as is the case when considering competing causes of failure in equipment or death for a patient.
[src:random-walk-theory/first-hitting-time-model] Practical applications of theoretical models for first hitting times often involve regression structures.
[src:random-walk-theory/first-hitting-time-model] When first hitting time models are equipped with regression structures, accommodating covariate data, we call such regression structure *threshold regression*.
[src:random-walk-theory/first-hitting-time-model] The threshold state, parameters of the process, and even time scale may depend on corresponding covariates.
[src:random-walk-theory/first-hitting-time-model] Threshold regression as applied to time-to-event data has emerged since the start of this century and has grown rapidly, as described in a 2006 survey article and its references.
[src:random-walk-theory/first-hitting-time-model] Connections between threshold regression models derived from first hitting times and the ubiquitous Cox proportional hazards regression model was investigated in.
[src:random-walk-theory/first-hitting-time-model] Applications of threshold regression range over many fields, including the physical and natural sciences, engineering, social sciences, economics and business, agriculture, health and medicine.
[src:random-walk-theory/first-hitting-time-model] In many real world applications, a first-hitting-time (FHT) model has three underlying components: (1) a *parent stochastic process* $\{X(t)\}\,\,$ , which might be latent, (2) a *threshold* (or the barrier) and (3) a *time scale*.
[src:random-walk-theory/first-hitting-time-model] The first hitting time is defined as the time when the stochastic process first reaches the threshold.
[src:random-walk-theory/first-hitting-time-model] It is very important to distinguish whether the sample path of the parent process is latent (i.e., unobservable) or observable, and such distinction is a characteristic of the FHT model.
[src:random-walk-theory/first-hitting-time-model] By far, latent processes are most common.
[src:random-walk-theory/first-hitting-time-model] To give an example, we can use a Wiener process $\{X(t),t\geq 0\,\}\,$ as the parent stochastic process.
[src:random-walk-theory/first-hitting-time-model] Such Wiener process can be defined with the mean parameter ${\mu }\,\,$ , the variance parameter ${\sigma ^{2}}\,\,$ , and the initial value $X(0)=x_{0}>0\,$ .
[src:random-walk-theory/first-hitting-time-model] The time scale of the stochastic process may be calendar or clock time or some more operational measure of time progression, such as mileage of a car, accumulated wear and tear on a machine component or accumulated exposure to toxic fumes.
[src:random-walk-theory/first-hitting-time-model] In many applications, the stochastic process describing the system state is latent or unobservable and its properties must be inferred indirectly from censored time-to-event data and/or readings taken over time on correlated processes, such as marker processes.
[src:random-walk-theory/first-hitting-time-model] The word ‘regression’ in threshold regression refers to first-hitting-time models in which one or more regression structures are inserted into the model in order to connect model parameters to explanatory variables or covariates.
[src:random-walk-theory/first-hitting-time-model] The parameters given regression structures may be parameters of the stochastic process, the threshold state and/or the time scale itself.
[src:random-walk-theory/gambler-s-ruin] In statistics, **gambler's ruin** is the fact that a gambler playing a game with non-positive expected value will eventually go bankrupt, regardless of their betting system.
[src:random-walk-theory/gambler-s-ruin] The concept was initially stated: A persistent gambler who raises his bet to a fixed fraction of the gambler's bankroll after a win, but does not reduce it after a loss, will eventually and inevitably go broke, even if each bet has a positive expected value.
[src:random-walk-theory/gambler-s-ruin] Another statement of the concept is that a persistent gambler with finite wealth, playing a fair game (that is, each bet has expected value of zero to both sides) will eventually and inevitably go broke against an opponent with infinite wealth.
[src:random-walk-theory/gambler-s-ruin] Such a situation can be modeled by a random walk on the real number line.
[src:random-walk-theory/gambler-s-ruin] In that context, it is probable that the gambler will, with virtual certainty, return to their point of origin, which means going broke, and is ruined an infinite number of times if the random walk continues forever.
[src:random-walk-theory/gambler-s-ruin] This is a corollary of a general theorem by Christiaan Huygens, which is also known as gambler's ruin.
[src:random-walk-theory/gambler-s-ruin] That theorem shows how to compute the probability of each player winning a series of bets that continues until one's entire initial stake is lost, given the initial stakes of the two players and the constant probability of winning.
[src:random-walk-theory/gambler-s-ruin] This is the oldest *mathematical* idea that goes by the name gambler's ruin, but not the first idea to which the name was applied.
[src:random-walk-theory/gambler-s-ruin] The term's common usage today is another corollary to Huygens's result.
[src:random-walk-theory/gambler-s-ruin] The concept has specific relevance for gamblers.
[src:random-walk-theory/gambler-s-ruin] However it also leads to mathematical theorems with wide application and many related results in probability and statistics.
[src:random-walk-theory/gambler-s-ruin] Huygens's result in particular led to important advances in the mathematical theory of probability.
[src:random-walk-theory/gambler-s-ruin] The earliest known mention of the gambler's ruin problem is a letter from Blaise Pascal to Pierre Fermat in 1656 (two years after the more famous correspondence on the problem of points).
[src:random-walk-theory/gambler-s-ruin] This is the classic gambler's ruin formulation: two players begin with fixed stakes, transferring points until one or the other is "ruined" by getting to zero points.
[src:random-walk-theory/gambler-s-ruin] However, the term "gambler's ruin" was not applied until many years later.
[src:random-walk-theory/gambler-s-ruin] The gambler's ruin problem is often applied to gamblers with finite capital playing against a bookie or casino assumed to have an “infinite” or much larger amount of capital available.
[src:random-walk-theory/gambler-s-ruin] It can then be proven that the probability of the gambler's eventual ruin tends to 1 even in the scenario where the game is fair or what mathematically is defined as a martingale.
[src:random-walk-theory/gambler-s-ruin] Let d be the amount of money a gambler has at their disposal at any moment, and let N be any positive integer.
[src:random-walk-theory/gambler-s-ruin] Suppose that they raise their stake to ${\frac {d}{N}}$ when they win, but do not reduce their stake when they lose (a not uncommon pattern among real gamblers).
[src:random-walk-theory/gambler-s-ruin] Under this betting scheme, it will take at most *N* losing bets in a row to bankrupt them.
[src:random-walk-theory/gambler-s-ruin] If their probability of winning each bet is less than 1 (if it is 1, then they are no gambler), they are virtually certain to eventually lose *N* bets in a row, however big *N* is.
[src:random-walk-theory/gambler-s-ruin] It is not necessary that they follow the precise rule, just that they increase their bet fast enough as they win.
[src:random-walk-theory/gambler-s-ruin] This is true even if the expected value of each bet is positive.
[src:random-walk-theory/gambler-s-ruin] The gambler playing a fair game (with probability ${\frac {1}{2}}$ of winning) will eventually either go broke or double their wealth.
[src:random-walk-theory/gambler-s-ruin] By symmetry, they have a ${\frac {1}{2}}$ chance of going broke before doubling their money.
[src:random-walk-theory/gambler-s-ruin] If they double their money, they repeat this process and they again have a ${\frac {1}{2}}$ chance of doubling their money before going broke.
[src:random-walk-theory/gambler-s-ruin] After the second process, they have a $\left({\frac {1}{2}}\right)^{2}={\frac {1}{4}}$ chance that they have not gone broke yet.
[src:random-walk-theory/gambler-s-ruin] Continuing this way, their chance of not going broke after n processes is $\left({\frac {1}{2}}\right)^{n}$ , which approaches 0 , and their chance of going broke after n successive processes is $\sum _{i=1}^{n}\left({\frac {1}{2}}\right)^{i}$ which approaches 1 .
[src:random-walk-theory/gambler-s-ruin] Huygens's result is illustrated in the next section.
[src:random-walk-theory/gambler-s-ruin] The eventual fate of a player at a game with negative expected value cannot be better than the player at a fair game, so they will go broke as well.
[src:random-walk-theory/gambler-s-ruin] Consider a coin-flipping game with two players where each player has a 50% chance of winning with each flip of the coin.
[src:random-walk-theory/gambler-s-ruin] After each flip of the coin the loser transfers one penny to the winner.
[src:random-walk-theory/gambler-s-ruin] The game ends when one player has all the pennies.
[src:random-walk-theory/gambler-s-ruin] If there are no other limitations on the number of flips, the probability that the game will eventually end this way is 1.
[src:random-walk-theory/gambler-s-ruin] Any given finite string of heads and tails will eventually be flipped with certainty: the probability of not seeing this string, while high at first, decays exponentially.
[src:random-walk-theory/gambler-s-ruin] Two examples of this are if one player has more pennies than the other; and if both players have the same number of pennies.
[src:random-walk-theory/gambler-s-ruin] It follows that even with equal odds of winning the player that starts with fewer pennies is more likely to fail.
[src:random-walk-theory/gambler-s-ruin] Alternately, this can be shown as follows: Consider the probability of player 1 experiencing gamblers ruin having started with $n>1$ amount of money, $P(R_{n})$ .
[src:random-walk-theory/gambler-s-ruin] where W denotes the event that player 1 wins the first bet.
[src:random-walk-theory/gambler-s-ruin] Also $P(R_{n}|W)=P(R_{n+1})$ is the probability that player 1 experiences gambler's ruin having started with $n+1$ amount of money: and $P(R_{n}\mid {\bar {W}})=P(R_{n-1})$ is the probability that player 1 experiences gambler's ruin having started with $n-1$ amount of money.
[src:random-walk-theory/gambler-s-ruin] Feller (1970), *An introduction to probability theory and its applications*, 3rd ed.
[src:random-walk-theory/gambler-s-ruin] The above-described problem (2 players) is a special case of the so-called N-Player Ruin problem.
[src:random-walk-theory/gambler-s-ruin] Here $N\geq 2$ players with initial capital $x_{1},x_{2},\ldots ,x_{N}$ dollars, respectively, play a sequence of (arbitrary) independent games and win and lose certain amounts of dollars from and to each other according to fixed rules.
[src:random-walk-theory/gambler-s-ruin] The sequence of games ends as soon as at least one player is ruined.
[src:random-walk-theory/gambler-s-ruin] Standard Markov chain methods can be applied to solve this more general problem in principle, but the computations quickly become prohibitive as soon as the number of players or their initial capitals increase.
[src:random-walk-theory/gambler-s-ruin] For $N=2$ and large initial capitals $x_{1},x_{2}$ the solution can be well approximated by using two-dimensional Brownian motion.
[src:random-walk-theory/gambler-s-ruin] (For $N\geq 3$ this is not possible.) In practice the true problem is to find the solution for the typical cases of $N\geq 3$ and limited initial capital.
[src:random-walk-theory/gambler-s-ruin] Swan (2006) proposed an algorithm based on matrix-analytic methods (Folding Algorithm for ruin problems) which significantly reduces the order of the computational task in such cases.
[src:random-walk-theory/loop-erased-random-walk] In mathematics, **loop-erased random walk** is a model for a random simple path with important applications in combinatorics, physics and quantum field theory.
[src:random-walk-theory/loop-erased-random-walk] It is intimately connected to the **uniform spanning tree**, a model for a random tree.
[src:random-walk-theory/loop-erased-random-walk] It is a case of the more general topic of *random walks*.
[src:random-walk-theory/loop-erased-random-walk] Assume *G* is some graph and $\gamma$ is some path of length *n* on *G*.
[src:random-walk-theory/loop-erased-random-walk] In other words, $\gamma (1),\dots ,\gamma (n)$ are vertices of *G* such that $\gamma (i)$ and $\gamma (i+1)$ are connected by an edge.
[src:random-walk-theory/loop-erased-random-walk] Then the **loop erasure** of $\gamma$ is a new simple path created by erasing all the loops of $\gamma$ in chronological order.
[src:random-walk-theory/loop-erased-random-walk] where "max" here means up to the length of the path $\gamma$ .
[src:random-walk-theory/loop-erased-random-walk] The induction stops when for some $i_{j}$ we have $\gamma (i_{j})=\gamma (n)$ .
[src:random-walk-theory/loop-erased-random-walk] Assume the induction stops at *J* i.e. $\gamma (i_{J})=\gamma (n)$ is the last $i_{J}$ .
[src:random-walk-theory/loop-erased-random-walk] Now let *G* be some graph, let *v* be a vertex of *G*, and let *R* be a random walk on *G* starting from *v*.
[src:random-walk-theory/loop-erased-random-walk] Then the **loop-erased random walk** until time *T* is LE(*R*([1,*T*])).
[src:random-walk-theory/loop-erased-random-walk] In other words, take *R* from its beginning until *T* — that's a (random) path — erase all the loops in chronological order as above — you get a random simple path.
[src:random-walk-theory/loop-erased-random-walk] The stopping time *T* may be fixed, i.e. one may perform *n* steps and then loop-erase.
[src:random-walk-theory/loop-erased-random-walk] However, it is usually more natural to take *T* to be the hitting time in some set.
[src:random-walk-theory/loop-erased-random-walk] For example, let *G* be the graph **Z**2 and let *R* be a random walk starting from the point (0,0).
[src:random-walk-theory/loop-erased-random-walk] Let *T* be the time when *R* first hits the circle of radius 100 (we mean here of course a *discretized* circle).
[src:random-walk-theory/loop-erased-random-walk] LE(*R*) is called the loop-erased random walk starting at (0,0) and stopped at the circle.
[src:random-walk-theory/loop-erased-random-walk] For any graph *G*, a spanning tree of *G* is a subgraph of *G* containing all vertices and some of the edges, which is a tree, i.e. connected and with no cycles.
[src:random-walk-theory/loop-erased-random-walk] A spanning tree chosen randomly from among all possible spanning trees with equal probability is called a uniform spanning tree.
[src:random-walk-theory/loop-erased-random-walk] There are typically exponentially many spanning trees (too many to generate them all and then choose one randomly); instead, uniform spanning trees can be generated more efficiently by an algorithm called Wilson's algorithm which uses loop-erased random walks.
[src:random-walk-theory/loop-erased-random-walk] The algorithm proceeds according to the following steps.
[src:random-walk-theory/loop-erased-random-walk] First, construct a single-vertex tree *T* by choosing (arbitrarily) one vertex.
[src:random-walk-theory/loop-erased-random-walk] Then, while the tree *T* constructed so far does not yet include all of the vertices of the graph, let *v* be an arbitrary vertex that is not in *T*, perform a loop-erased random walk from *v* until reaching a vertex in *T*, and add the resulting path to *T*.
[src:random-walk-theory/loop-erased-random-walk] Repeating this process until all vertices are included produces a uniformly distributed tree, regardless of the arbitrary choices of vertices at each step.
[src:random-walk-theory/loop-erased-random-walk] A connection in the other direction is also true.
[src:random-walk-theory/loop-erased-random-walk] If *v* and *w* are two vertices in *G* then, in any spanning tree, they are connected by a unique path.
[src:random-walk-theory/loop-erased-random-walk] Taking this path in the *uniform* spanning tree gives a random simple path.
[src:random-walk-theory/loop-erased-random-walk] It turns out that the distribution of this path is identical to the distribution of the loop-erased random walk starting at *v* and stopped at *w*.
[src:random-walk-theory/loop-erased-random-walk] This fact can be used to justify the correctness of Wilson's algorithm.
[src:random-walk-theory/loop-erased-random-walk] Another corollary is that loop-erased random walk is symmetric in its start and end points.
[src:random-walk-theory/loop-erased-random-walk] More precisely, the distribution of the loop-erased random walk starting at *v* and stopped at *w* is identical to the distribution of the reversal of loop-erased random walk starting at *w* and stopped at *v*.
[src:random-walk-theory/loop-erased-random-walk] Loop-erasing a random walk and the reverse walk do not, in general, give the same result, but according to this result the distributions of the two loop-erased walks are identical.
[src:random-walk-theory/loop-erased-random-walk] Another representation of loop-erased random walk stems from solutions of the discrete Laplace equation.
[src:random-walk-theory/loop-erased-random-walk] Let *G* again be a graph and let *v* and *w* be two vertices in *G*.
[src:random-walk-theory/loop-erased-random-walk] Construct a random path from *v* to *w* inductively using the following procedure.
[src:random-walk-theory/loop-erased-random-walk] Assume we have already defined $\gamma (1),...,\gamma (n)$ .
[src:random-walk-theory/loop-erased-random-walk] Where a function *f* on a graph is discretely harmonic at a point *x* if *f*(*x*) equals the average of *f* on the neighbors of *x*.
[src:random-walk-theory/loop-erased-random-walk] With *f* defined choose $\gamma (n+1)$ using *f* at the neighbors of $\gamma (n)$ as weights.
[src:random-walk-theory/loop-erased-random-walk] Continuing this process, recalculating *f* at each step, will result in a random simple path from *v* to *w*; the distribution of this path is identical to that of a loop-erased random walk from *v* to *w*.
[src:random-walk-theory/loop-erased-random-walk] An alternative view is that the distribution of a loop-erased random walk conditioned to start in some path β is identical to the loop-erasure of a random walk conditioned not to hit β.
[src:random-walk-theory/loop-erased-random-walk] This property is often referred to as the **Markov property** of loop-erased random walk (though the relation to the usual Markov property is somewhat vague).
[src:random-walk-theory/loop-erased-random-walk] It is important to notice that while the proof of the equivalence is quite easy, models which involve dynamically changing harmonic functions or measures are typically extremely difficult to analyze.
[src:random-walk-theory/loop-erased-random-walk] Practically nothing is known about the p-Laplacian walk or diffusion-limited aggregation.
[src:random-walk-theory/loop-erased-random-walk] Another somewhat related model is the harmonic explorer.
[src:random-walk-theory/loop-erased-random-walk] Finally there is another link that should be mentioned: Kirchhoff's theorem relates the number of spanning trees of a graph *G* to the eigenvalues of the discrete Laplacian.
[src:random-walk-theory/loop-erased-random-walk] Let *d* be the dimension, which we will assume to be at least 2.
[src:random-walk-theory/loop-erased-random-walk] This is an infinite graph with degree 2*d* when you connect each point to its nearest neighbors.
[src:random-walk-theory/loop-erased-random-walk] From now on we will consider loop-erased random walk on this graph or its subgraphs.
[src:random-walk-theory/loop-erased-random-walk] The easiest case to analyze is dimension 5 and above.
[src:random-walk-theory/loop-erased-random-walk] In this case it turns out that there the intersections are only local.
[src:random-walk-theory/loop-erased-random-walk] A calculation shows that if one takes a random walk of length *n*, its loop-erasure has length of the same order of magnitude, i.e.
[src:random-walk-theory/loop-erased-random-walk] Scaling accordingly, it turns out that loop-erased random walk converges (in an appropriate sense) to Brownian motion as *n* goes to infinity.
[src:random-walk-theory/loop-erased-random-walk] Dimension 4 is more complicated, but the general picture is still true.
[src:random-walk-theory/loop-erased-random-walk] It turns out that the loop-erasure of a random walk of length *n* has approximately $n/\log ^{1/3}n$ vertices, but again, after scaling (that takes into account the logarithmic factor) the loop-erased walk converges to Brownian motion.
[src:random-walk-theory/loop-erased-random-walk] In two dimensions, arguments from conformal field theory and simulation results led to a number of exciting conjectures.
[src:random-walk-theory/loop-erased-random-walk] Assume *D* is some simply connected domain in the plane and *x* is a point in *D*.
[src:random-walk-theory/loop-erased-random-walk] that is, a grid of side length ε restricted to *D*.
[src:random-walk-theory/loop-erased-random-walk] Let *v* be the vertex of *G* closest to *x*.
[src:random-walk-theory/loop-erased-random-walk] Examine now a loop-erased random walk starting from *v* and stopped when hitting the "boundary" of *G*, i.e. the vertices of *G* which correspond to the boundary of *D*.
[src:random-walk-theory/loop-erased-random-walk] The first attack at these conjectures came from the direction of **domino tilings**.
[src:random-walk-theory/loop-erased-random-walk] Taking a spanning tree of *G* and adding to it its planar dual one gets a domino tiling of a special derived graph (call it *H*).
[src:random-walk-theory/loop-erased-random-walk] Each vertex of *H* corresponds to a vertex, edge or face of *G*, and the edges of *H* show which vertex lies on which edge and which edge on which face.
[src:random-walk-theory/loop-erased-random-walk] It turns out that taking a uniform spanning tree of *G* leads to a uniformly distributed random domino tiling of *H*.
[src:random-walk-theory/loop-erased-random-walk] The number of domino tilings of a graph can be calculated using the determinant of special matrices, which allow to connect it to the discrete Green function which is approximately conformally invariant.
[src:random-walk-theory/loop-erased-random-walk] These arguments allowed to show that certain measurables of loop-erased random walk are (in the limit) conformally invariant, and that the expected number of vertices in a loop-erased random walk stopped at a circle of radius *r* is of the order of $r^{5/4}$ .
[src:random-walk-theory/loop-erased-random-walk] In 2002 these conjectures were resolved (positively) using stochastic Löwner evolution.
[src:random-walk-theory/loop-erased-random-walk] Very roughly, it is a stochastic conformally invariant ordinary differential equation which allows to catch the Markov property of loop-erased random walk (and many other probabilistic processes).
[src:random-walk-theory/loop-erased-random-walk] The scaling limit exists and is invariant under rotations and dilations.
[src:random-walk-theory/loop-erased-random-walk] where ε, *c* and *C* are some positive numbers (the numbers can, in principle, be calculated from the proofs, but the author did not do it).
[src:random-walk-theory/loop-erased-random-walk] This suggests that the scaling limit should have Hausdorff dimension between $1+\varepsilon$ and 5/3 almost surely.
[src:random-walk-theory/loop-erased-random-walk] Numerical experiments show that it should be $1.62400\pm 0.00005$ .
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] In probability theory and statistics, a **Markov chain** or **Markov process** is a stochastic process describing a sequence of possible events in which the probability of each event depends only on the state attained in the previous event.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] Informally, this may be thought of as, "What happens next depends only on the state of affairs *now*." A countably infinite sequence, in which the chain moves state at discrete time steps, gives a discrete-time Markov chain (DTMC).
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] A continuous-time process is called a continuous-time Markov chain (CTMC).
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] Markov processes are named in honor of the Russian mathematician Andrey Markov.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] Markov chains have many applications as statistical models of real-world processes.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] The adjectives *Markovian* and *Markov* are used to describe something that is related to a Markov process.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] A Markov process is a stochastic process that satisfies the Markov property (sometimes characterized as "memorylessness").
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] In simpler terms, it is a process for which predictions can be made regarding future outcomes based solely on its present state and—most importantly—such predictions are just as good as the ones that could be made knowing the process's full history.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] In other words, conditional on the present state of the system, its future and past states are independent.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] A Markov chain is a type of Markov process that has either a discrete state space or a discrete index set (often representing time), but the precise definition of a Markov chain varies.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] The system's state space and time parameter index need to be specified.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] Note that there is no definitive agreement in the literature on the use of some of the terms that signify special cases of Markov processes.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] Usually the term "Markov chain" is reserved for a process with a discrete set of times, that is, a **discrete-time Markov chain (DTMC)**, but a few authors use the term "Markov process" to refer to a **continuous-time Markov chain (CTMC)** without explicit mention.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] In addition, there are other extensions of Markov processes that are referred to as such but do not necessarily fall within any of these four categories (see Markov model).
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] Moreover, the time index need not necessarily be real-valued; like with the state space, there are conceivable processes that move through index sets with other mathematical constructs.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] Notice that the general state space continuous-time Markov chain is general to such a degree that it has no designated term.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] While the time parameter is usually discrete, the state space of a Markov chain does not have any generally agreed-on restrictions: the term may refer to a process on an arbitrary state space.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] However, many applications of Markov chains employ finite or countably infinite state spaces, which have a more straightforward statistical analysis.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] Besides time-index and state-space parameters, there are many other variations, extensions and generalizations (see Variations).
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] For simplicity, most of this article concentrates on the discrete-time, discrete state-space case, unless mentioned otherwise.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] The changes of state of the system are called transitions.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] The probabilities associated with various state changes are called transition probabilities.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] The process is characterized by a state space, a transition matrix describing the probabilities of particular transitions, and an initial state (or initial distribution) across the state space.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] By convention, we assume all possible states and transitions have been included in the definition of the process, so there is always a next state, and the process does not terminate.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] A discrete-time random process involves a system which is in a certain state at each step, with the state changing randomly between steps.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] The steps are often thought of as moments in time, but they can equally well refer to physical distance or any other discrete measurement.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] Formally, the steps are the integers or natural numbers, and the random process is a mapping of these to states.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] The Markov property states that the conditional probability distribution for the system at the next step (and in fact at all future steps) depends only on the current state of the system, and not additionally on the state of the system at previous steps.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] Since the system changes randomly, it is generally impossible to predict with certainty the state of a Markov chain at a given point in the future.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] However, the statistical properties of the system's future can be predicted.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] In many applications, it is these statistical properties that are important.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] Andrey Markov studied Markov processes in the early 20th century, publishing his first paper on the topic in 1906.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] Markov processes in continuous time were discovered long before his work in the early 20th century in the form of the Poisson process.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] Markov was interested in studying an extension of independent random sequences, motivated by a disagreement with Pavel Nekrasov who claimed independence was necessary for the weak law of large numbers to hold.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] Markov later used Markov chains to study the distribution of vowels in Eugene Onegin, written by Alexander Pushkin, and proved a central limit theorem for such chains.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] In 1912 Henri Poincaré studied Markov chains on finite groups with an aim to study card shuffling.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] Other early uses of Markov chains include a diffusion model, introduced by Paul and Tatyana Ehrenfest in 1907, and a branching process, introduced by Francis Galton and Henry William Watson in 1873, preceding the work of Markov.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] After the work of Galton and Watson, it was later revealed that their branching process had been independently discovered and studied around three decades earlier by Irénée-Jules Bienaymé.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] Starting in 1928, Maurice Fréchet became interested in Markov chains, eventually resulting in him publishing in 1938 a detailed study on Markov chains.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] Andrey Kolmogorov developed in a 1931 paper a large part of the early theory of continuous-time Markov processes.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] Kolmogorov was partly inspired by Louis Bachelier's 1900 work on fluctuations in the stock market as well as Norbert Wiener's work on Einstein's model of Brownian movement.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] He introduced and studied a particular set of Markov processes known as diffusion processes, where he derived a set of differential equations describing the processes.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] Independent of Kolmogorov's work, Sydney Chapman derived in a 1928 paper an equation, now called the Chapman–Kolmogorov equation, in a less mathematically rigorous way than Kolmogorov, while studying Brownian movement.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] The differential equations are now called the Kolmogorov equations or the Kolmogorov–Chapman equations.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] Other mathematicians who contributed significantly to the foundations of Markov processes include William Feller, starting in 1930s, and then later Eugene Dynkin, starting in the 1950s.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] Suppose that there is a coin purse containing five coins worth 25¢ (quarters), five coins worth 10¢ (dimes) and five coins worth 5¢ (nickels).
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] One by one, coins are randomly drawn from the purse and are set on a table.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] If $X_{n}$ represents the total value of the coins set on the table after n draws, with $X_{0}=0$ , then the sequence $\{X_{n}:n\in \mathbb {N} \}$ is *not* a Markov process.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] To see why this is the case, suppose that in the first six draws, all five nickels and a quarter are drawn.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] If we know not just $X_{6}$ , but the earlier values as well, then we can determine which coins have been drawn, and we know that the next coin will not be a nickel; so we can determine that $X_{7}\geq \$0.60$ with probability 1.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] But if we do not know the earlier values, then based only on the value $X_{6}$ we might guess that we had drawn four dimes and two nickels, in which case it would certainly be possible to draw another nickel next.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] Thus, our guesses about $X_{7}$ are impacted by our knowledge of values prior to $X_{6}$ .
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] However, it is possible to model this scenario as a Markov process.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] Instead of defining $X_{n}$ to represent the *total value* of the coins on the table, we could define $X_{n}$ to represent the *count* of the various coin types on the table.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] For instance, $X_{6}=1,0,5$ could be defined to represent the state where there is one quarter, zero dimes, and five nickels on the table after 6 one-by-one draws.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] This new model could be represented by $6\times 6\times 6=216$ possible states, where each state represents the number of coins of each type (from 0 to 5) that are on the table.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] Suppose that the first draw results in state $X_{1}=0,1,0$ .
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] The probability of achieving $X_{2}$ now depends on $X_{1}$ ; for example, the state $X_{2}=1,0,1$ is not possible.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] After the second draw, the third draw depends on which coins have so far been drawn, but no longer only on the coins that were drawn for the first state (since probabilistically important information has since been added to the scenario).
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] In this way, the likelihood of the $X_{n}=i,j,k$ state depends exclusively on the outcome of the $X_{n-1}=\ell ,m,p$ state.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] The possible values of *X**i* form a countable set *S* called the state space of the chain.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] Since each row of **P** sums to one and all elements are non-negative, **P** is a right stochastic matrix.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] is a normalized ( ${\textstyle \sum _{i}\pi _{i}=1}$ ) multiple of a left eigenvector **e** of the transition matrix **P** with an eigenvalue of 1.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] If there is more than one unit eigenvector then a weighted sum of the corresponding stationary states is also a stationary state.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] But for a Markov chain one is usually more interested in a stationary state that is the limit of the sequence of distributions for some initial distribution.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] The values of a stationary distribution $\textstyle \pi _{i}$ are associated with the state space of **P** and its eigenvectors have their relative proportions preserved.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] Since the components of π are positive and the constraint that their sum is unity can be rewritten as ${\textstyle \sum _{i}1\cdot \pi _{i}=1}$ we see that the dot product of π with a vector whose components are all 1 is unity and that π lies on a simplex.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] If the Markov chain is time-homogeneous, then the transition matrix **P** is the same after each step, so the *k*-step transition probability can be computed as the *k*-th power of the transition matrix, **P***k*.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] If the Markov chain is irreducible and aperiodic, then there is a unique stationary distribution π.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] where **1** is the column vector with all entries equal to 1.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] This is stated by the Perron–Frobenius theorem.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] If, by whatever means, ${\textstyle \lim _{k\to \infty }\mathbf {P} ^{k}}$ is found, then the stationary distribution of the Markov chain in question can be easily determined for any starting distribution, as will be explained below.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] Because there are a number of different special cases to consider, the process of finding this limit if it exists can be a lengthy task.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] However, there are many techniques that can assist in finding this limit.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] where **I***n* is the identity matrix of size *n*, and **0***n*,*n* is the zero matrix of size *n*×*n*.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] Multiplying together stochastic matrices always yields another stochastic matrix, so **Q** must be a stochastic matrix (see the definition above).
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] It is sometimes sufficient to use the matrix equation above and the fact that **Q** is a stochastic matrix to solve for **Q**.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] Here is one method for doing so: first, define the function *f*(**A**) to return the matrix **A** with its right-most column replaced with all 1's.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] One thing to notice is that if **P** has an element **P***i*,*i* on its main diagonal that is equal to 1 and the *i*th row or column is otherwise filled with 0's, then that row or column will remain unchanged in all of the subsequent powers **P***k*.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] Hence, the *i*th row or column of **Q** will have the 1 and the 0's in the same positions as in **P**.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] As stated earlier, from the equation ${\boldsymbol {\pi }}={\boldsymbol {\pi }}\mathbf {P} ,$ (if exists) the stationary (or steady state) distribution **π** is a left eigenvector of row stochastic matrix **P**.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] Then assuming that **P** is diagonalizable or equivalently that **P** has *n* linearly independent eigenvectors, speed of convergence is elaborated as follows.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] Let **U** be the matrix of eigenvectors (each normalized to having an L2 norm equal to 1) where each column is a left eigenvector of **P** and let **Σ** be the diagonal matrix of left eigenvalues of **P**, that is, **Σ** = diag(*λ*1,*λ*2,*λ*3,...,*λ**n*).
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] Since **P** is a row stochastic matrix, its largest left eigenvalue is 1.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] If there is a unique stationary distribution, then the largest eigenvalue and the corresponding eigenvector is unique too (because there is no other **π** which solves the stationary distribution equation above).
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] Let **u***i* be the *i*-th column of **U** matrix, that is, **u***i* is the left eigenvector of **P** corresponding to λ*i*.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] If we multiply **x** with **P** from right and continue this operation with the results, in the end we get the stationary distribution **π**.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] Since **π** is parallel to **u**1(normalized by L2 norm) and **π**(*k*) is a probability vector, **π**(*k*) approaches to **a**1 **u**1 = **π** as *k* → ∞ with a speed in the order of *λ*2/*λ*1 exponentially.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] This follows because $|\lambda _{2}|\geq \cdots \geq |\lambda _{n}|,$ hence *λ*2/*λ*1 is the dominant term.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] The smaller the ratio is, the faster the convergence is.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] Random noise in the state distribution **π** can also speed up this convergence to the stationary distribution.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] A continuous-time Markov chain $(X_{t})_{t\geq 0}$ is defined by a finite or countable state space *S*, a transition rate matrix *Q* with dimensions equal to that of the state space and initial probability distribution defined on the state space.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] For *i* ≠ *j*, the elements *q**ij* are non-negative and describe the rate of the process transitions from state *i* to state *j*.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] The elements *q**ii* are chosen such that each row of the transition rate matrix sums to zero, while the row-sums of a probability transition matrix in a (discrete) Markov chain are all equal to one.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] There are three equivalent definitions of the process.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] Let $X_{t}$ be the random variable describing the state of the process at time *t*, and assume the process is in a state *i* at time *t*.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] Then, knowing $X_{t}=i$ , $X_{t+h}=j$ is independent of previous values $\left(X_{s}:s<t\right)$ , and as *h* → 0 for all *j* and for all *t*, $\Pr(X(t+h)=j\mid X(t)=i)=\delta _{ij}+q_{ij}h+o(h),$ where $\delta _{ij}$ is the Kronecker delta, using the little-o notation.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] The $q_{ij}$ can be seen as measuring how quickly the transition from *i* to *j* happens.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] Define a discrete-time Markov chain *Y**n* to describe the *n*th jump of the process and variables *S*1, *S*2, *S*3, ... to describe holding times in each of the states where *S**i* follows the exponential distribution with rate parameter −*q**Y**i**Y**i*.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] with initial condition P(0) is the identity matrix.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] "Locally interacting Markov chains" are Markov chains with an evolution that takes into account the state of other Markov chains.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] This corresponds to the situation when the state space has a (Cartesian-) product form.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] See interacting particle system and stochastic cellular automata (probabilistic cellular automata).
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] See for instance *Interaction of Markov Processes* or.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] Many results for discrete-time Markov chains with finite state space can be generalized to chains with uncountable state space through Harris chains.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] The use of Markov chains in Markov chain Monte Carlo methods covers cases where the process follows a continuous state space.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] The definition of Markov processes in continuous time with general state space is more technical than the above.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] A continuous-time Markov process $X=(X_{t})_{t\geq 0}$ is a stochastic process adapted to a filtration $\mathbb {F} =({\mathcal {F}}_{t})_{t\geq 0}$ with values in a locally compact Polish space $(S,{\mathcal {B}}(S))$ (e.g., $(\mathbb {R} ,{\mathcal {B}}(\mathbb {R} ))$ ).
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] The latter essentially ensures that the conditional expectations of $X_{t}$ are regular, which, in simple terms, means that they behave "nicely".
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] The function $(t,x,A)\mapsto P_{t}(x,A)$ is the so-called *transition function* of X and $(P_{t})_{t\geq 0}$ the *transition semigroup* of the process.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] Transition functions are generalizations of the transition matrices used in the setting with finite state space.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] where $\delta _{x}$ is the Dirac-measure in x , and $X:\Omega \times [0,\infty )\to S$ .
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] Or, if no probability measure P has been specified, the above equation defines a measure $P^{x}:=P(\cdot \mid X_{0}=x)$ on $\sigma (X_{s}:s\geq 0)$ under which the process X started in x is a Markov process by construction.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] In other words, Markov processes can be defined either as stochastic processes X on a filtered probability space, or indirectly in terms of a transition semigroup (i.e., the transition probabilities of the process), which induces a probability space under which X has the Markov property.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] Two states are said to *communicate* with each other if both are reachable from one another by a sequence of transitions that have positive probability.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] This is an equivalence relation which yields a set of communicating classes.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] A class is *closed* if the probability of leaving the class is zero.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] A Markov chain is *irreducible* if there is one communicating class, the state space.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] A state *i* has period *k* if *k* is the greatest common divisor of the number of transitions by which *i* can be reached, starting from *i*.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] The state is *periodic* if $k>1$ ; otherwise $k=1$ and the state is *aperiodic*.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] A state *i* is said to be *transient* if, starting from *i*, there is a non-zero probability that the chain will never return to *i*.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] It is called *recurrent* (or *persistent*) otherwise.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] State *i* is *positive recurrent* if $M_{i}$ is finite and *null recurrent* otherwise.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] Periodicity, transience, recurrence and positive and null recurrence are class properties — that is, if one state has the property then all states in its communicating class have the property.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] A state *i* is called *absorbing* if there are no outgoing transitions from the state.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] Since periodicity is a class property, if a Markov chain is irreducible, then all its states have the same period.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] In particular, if one state is aperiodic, then the whole Markov chain is aperiodic.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] If a finite Markov chain is irreducible, then all states are positive recurrent, and it has a unique stationary distribution given by $\pi _{i}=1/E[T_{i}]$ .
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] A state *i* is said to be *ergodic* if it is aperiodic and positive recurrent.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] In other words, a state *i* is ergodic if it is recurrent, has a period of 1, and has finite mean recurrence time.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] If all states in an irreducible Markov chain are ergodic, then the chain is said to be ergodic.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] Equivalently, there exists some integer k such that all entries of $M^{k}$ are positive.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] It can be shown that a finite state irreducible Markov chain is ergodic if it has an aperiodic state.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] A Markov chain with more than one state and just one out-going transition per state is either not irreducible or not aperiodic, hence cannot be ergodic.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] Some authors call any irreducible, positive recurrent Markov chains ergodic, even periodic ones.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] In fact, merely irreducible Markov chains correspond to ergodic processes, defined according to ergodic theory.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] Some authors call a matrix *primitive* if there exists some integer k such that all entries of $M^{k}$ are positive.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] The *index of primitivity*, or *exponent*, of a regular matrix, is the smallest k such that all entries of $M^{k}$ are positive.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] The exponent is purely a graph-theoretic property, since it depends only on whether each entry of M is zero or positive, and therefore can be found on a directed graph with $\mathrm {sign} (M)$ as its adjacency matrix.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] There are several combinatorial results about the exponent when there are finitely many states.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] If a Markov chain has a stationary distribution, then it can be converted to a measure-preserving dynamical system: Let the probability space be $\Omega =\Sigma ^{\mathbb {N} }$ , where $\Sigma$ is the set of all states for the Markov chain.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] Let the sigma-algebra on the probability space be generated by the cylinder sets.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] Let the probability measure be generated by the stationary distribution, and the Markov chain transition.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] Similarly we can construct such a dynamical system with $\Omega =\Sigma ^{\mathbb {Z} }$ instead.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] Since *irreducible* Markov chains with finite state spaces have a unique stationary distribution, the above construction is unambiguous for irreducible Markov chains.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] In ergodic theory, a measure-preserving dynamical system is called *ergodic* if any measurable subset S such that $T^{-1}(S)=S$ implies $S=\emptyset$ or $\Omega$ (up to a null set).
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] Given a Markov chain with a stationary distribution that is strictly positive on all states, the Markov chain is *irreducible* if its corresponding measure-preserving dynamical system is *ergodic*.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] In some cases, apparently non-Markovian processes may still have Markovian representations, constructed by expanding the concept of the "current" and "future" states.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] For example, let *X* be a non-Markovian process.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] Then define a process *Y*, such that each state of *Y* represents a time-interval of states of *X*.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] If *Y* has the Markov property, then it is a Markovian representation of *X*.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] An example of a non-Markovian process with a Markovian representation is an autoregressive time series of order greater than one.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] The *hitting time* is the time, starting in a given set of states, until the chain arrives in a given state or set of states.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] The distribution of such a time period has a phase type distribution.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] The simplest such distribution is that of a single exponentially distributed transition.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] For a general Markov process X in continuous time (a CTMC or a process with general state space), the reverse process ${\overleftarrow {X}}=(X_{T-t})_{t\in [0,T]}$ from a fixed time $T>0$ is again a Markov process.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] This follows directly from the Markov property: Informally speaking, the future and the past are independent given the present.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] Under time-reversal, their roles are just interchanged.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] However, the reverse process is not time-homogeneous in general.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] If X is a CTMC, then by Kelly's lemma ${\overleftarrow {X}}$ has the same stationary distribution as the forward process.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] A chain is said to be *reversible* if the reversed process is the same as the forward process (in distribution).
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] Kolmogorov's criterion states that the necessary and sufficient condition for a Markov chain to be reversible is that the product of transition rates around a closed loop must be the same in both directions.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] One method of finding the stationary probability distribution, π, of an ergodic continuous-time Markov chain, *Q*, is by first finding its **embedded Markov chain (EMC)**.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] Strictly speaking, the EMC is a regular discrete-time Markov chain, sometimes referred to as a **jump process**.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] Each element of the one-step transition probability matrix of the EMC, *S*, is denoted by *s**ij*, and represents the conditional probability of transitioning from state *i* into state *j*.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] where *I* is the identity matrix and diag(*Q*) is the diagonal matrix formed by selecting the main diagonal from the matrix *Q* and setting all other elements to zero.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] with $\varphi$ being a row vector, such that all elements in $\varphi$ are greater than 0 and $\|\varphi \|_{1}$ = 1.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] (*S* may be periodic, even if *Q* is not.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] Another discrete-time process that may be derived from a continuous-time Markov chain is a δ-skeleton—the (discrete-time) Markov chain formed by observing *X*(*t*) at intervals of δ units of time.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] The random variables *X*(0), *X*(δ), *X*(2δ), ... give the sequence of states visited by the δ-skeleton.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] Markov models are used to model changing systems.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] A Bernoulli scheme is a special case of a Markov chain where the transition probability matrix has identical rows, which means that the next state is independent of even the current state (in addition to being independent of the past states).
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] A Bernoulli scheme with only two possible states is known as a Bernoulli process.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] Note, however, by the Ornstein isomorphism theorem, that every aperiodic and irreducible Markov chain is isomorphic to a Bernoulli scheme; thus, one might equally claim that Markov chains are a "special case" of Bernoulli schemes.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] The isomorphism generally requires a complicated recoding.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] The isomorphism theorem is even a bit stronger: it states that *any* stationary stochastic process is isomorphic to a Bernoulli scheme; the Markov chain is just one such example.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] When the Markov matrix is replaced by the adjacency matrix of a finite graph, the resulting shift is termed a **topological Markov chain** or a **subshift of finite type**.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] A Markov matrix that is compatible with the adjacency matrix can then provide a measure on the subshift.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p01] Many chaotic dynamical systems are isomorphic to topological Markov chains; examples include diffeomorphisms of closed manifolds, the Prouhet–Thue–Morse system, the Chacon system, sofic systems, context-free systems and block-coding systems.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p02] Markov chains have been employed in a wide range of topics across the natural and social sciences, and in technological applications.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p02] For example, a thermodynamic state operates under a probability distribution that is difficult or expensive to acquire.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p02] Therefore, Markov Chain Monte Carlo method can be used to draw samples randomly from a black-box to approximate the probability distribution of attributes over a range of objects.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p02] Markov chains are used in lattice QCD simulations.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p02] The enzyme (E) binds a substrate (S) and produces a product (P).
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p02] Each reaction is a state transition in a Markov chain.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p02] A reaction network is a chemical system involving multiple reactions and chemical species.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p02] The simplest stochastic models of such networks treat the system as a continuous time Markov chain with the state being the number of molecules of each species and with reactions modeled as possible transitions of the chain.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p02] Markov chains and continuous-time Markov processes are useful in chemistry when physical systems closely approximate the Markov property.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p02] For example, imagine a large number *n* of molecules in solution in state A, each of which can undergo a chemical reaction to state B with a certain average rate.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p02] Perhaps the molecule is an enzyme, and the states refer to how it is folded.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p02] The state of any single enzyme follows a Markov chain, and since the molecules are essentially independent of each other, the number of molecules in state A or B at a time is *n* times the probability a given molecule is in that state.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p02] The classical model of enzyme activity, Michaelis–Menten kinetics, can be viewed as a Markov chain, where at each time step the reaction proceeds in some direction.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p02] While Michaelis-Menten is fairly straightforward, far more complicated reaction networks can also be modeled with Markov chains.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p02] An algorithm based on a Markov chain was also used to focus the fragment-based growth of chemicals in silico towards a desired class of compounds such as drugs or natural products.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p02] As a molecule is grown, a fragment is selected from the nascent molecule as the "current" state.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p02] It is not aware of its past (that is, it is not aware of what is already bonded to it).
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p02] It then transitions to the next state when a fragment is attached to it.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p02] The transition probabilities are trained on databases of authentic classes of compounds.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p02] Also, the growth (and composition) of copolymers may be modeled using Markov chains.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p02] Based on the reactivity ratios of the monomers that make up the growing polymer chain, the chain's composition may be calculated (for example, whether monomers tend to add in alternating fashion or in long runs of the same monomer).
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p02] Due to steric effects, second-order Markov effects may also play a role in the growth of some polymer chains.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p02] Similarly, it has been suggested that the crystallization and growth of some epitaxial superlattice oxide materials can be accurately described by Markov chains.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p02] Markov chains are used in various areas of biology.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p02] Markov chains are used throughout information processing.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p02] Such idealized models can capture many of the statistical regularities of systems.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p02] Even without describing the full structure of the system perfectly, such signal models can make possible very effective data compression through entropy encoding techniques such as arithmetic coding.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p02] They also allow effective state estimation and pattern recognition.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p02] Markov chains also play an important role in reinforcement learning.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p02] Markov chains are also the basis for hidden Markov models, which are an important tool in such diverse fields as telephone networks (which use the Viterbi algorithm for error correction), speech recognition and bioinformatics (such as in rearrangements detection).
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p02] The LZMA lossless data compression algorithm combines Markov chains with Lempel-Ziv compression to achieve very high compression ratios.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p02] Markov chains are the basis for the analytical treatment of queues (queueing theory).
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p02] Agner Krarup Erlang initiated the subject in 1917.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p02] This makes them critical for optimizing the performance of telecommunications networks, where messages must often compete for limited resources (such as bandwidth).
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p02] Numerous queueing models use continuous-time Markov chains.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p02] The PageRank of a webpage as used by Google is defined by a Markov chain.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p02] It is the probability to be at page i in the stationary distribution on the following Markov chain on all (known) webpages.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p02] If N is the number of known webpages, and a page i has $k_{i}$ outgoing links from it then it has transition probability ${\frac {\alpha }{k_{i}}}+{\frac {1-\alpha }{N}}$ for all pages that are linked to and ${\frac {1-\alpha }{N}}$ for all pages that are not linked to.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p02] The parameter $\alpha$ is taken to be about 0.85.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p02] Markov models have also been used to analyze web navigation behavior of users.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p02] A user's web link transition on a particular website can be modeled using first- or second-order Markov models and can be used to make predictions regarding future navigation and to personalize the web page for an individual user.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p02] Markov chain methods have also become very important for generating sequences of random numbers to accurately reflect very complicated desired probability distributions, via a process called Markov chain Monte Carlo (MCMC).
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p02] In recent years this has revolutionized the practicability of Bayesian inference methods, allowing a wide range of posterior distributions to be simulated and their parameters found numerically.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p02] Markov chains are used in finance and economics to model a variety of different phenomena, including the distribution of income, the size distribution of firms, asset prices and market crashes.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p02] Champernowne built a Markov chain model of the distribution of income in 1953.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p02] Simon and co-author Charles Bonini used a Markov chain model to derive a stationary Yule distribution of firm sizes.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p02] Louis Bachelier was the first to observe that stock prices followed a random walk.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p02] The random walk was later seen as evidence in favor of the efficient-market hypothesis and random walk models were popular in the literature of the 1960s.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p02] Regime-switching models of business cycles were popularized by James D.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p02] Hamilton (1989), who used a Markov chain to model switches between periods of high and low GDP growth (or, alternatively, economic expansions and recessions).
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p02] A more recent example is the Markov switching multifractal model of Laurent E.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p02] Fisher, which builds upon the convenience of earlier regime-switching models.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p02] It uses an arbitrarily large Markov chain to drive the level of volatility of asset returns.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p02] Dynamic macroeconomics makes heavy use of Markov chains.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p02] An example is using Markov chains to exogenously model prices of equity (stock) in a general equilibrium setting.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p02] Credit rating agencies produce annual tables of the transition probabilities for bonds of different credit ratings.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p02] Markov chains are generally used in describing path-dependent arguments, where current structural configurations condition future outcomes.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p02] An example is the reformulation of the idea, originally due to Karl Marx's *Das Kapital*, tying economic development to the rise of capitalism.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p02] Markov chains are employed in algorithmic music composition, particularly in software such as Csound, Max, and SuperCollider.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p02] In a first-order chain, the states of the system become note or pitch values, and a probability vector for each note is constructed, completing a transition probability matrix (see below).
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p02] An algorithm is constructed to produce output note values based on the transition matrix weightings, which could be MIDI note values, frequency (Hz), or any other desirable metric.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p02] A second-order Markov chain can be introduced by considering the current state *and* also the previous state, as indicated in the second table.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p02] Higher, *n*th-order chains tend to "group" particular notes together, while 'breaking off' into other patterns and sequences occasionally.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p02] These higher-order chains tend to generate results with a sense of phrasal structure, rather than the 'aimless wandering' produced by a first-order system.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p02] Markov chains can be used structurally, as in Xenakis's Analogique A and B.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p02] Markov chains are also used in systems which use a Markov model to react interactively to music input.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p02] Usually musical systems need to enforce specific control constraints on the finite-length sequences they generate, but control constraints are not compatible with Markov models, since they induce long-range dependencies that violate the Markov hypothesis of limited memory.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p02] In order to overcome this limitation, a new approach has been proposed.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p02] Markov chains can be used to model many games of chance.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p02] The children's games Snakes and Ladders and "Hi Ho!
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p02] Cherry-O", for example, are represented exactly by Markov chains.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p02] At each turn, the player starts in a given state (on a given square) and from there has fixed odds of moving to certain other states (squares).
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p02] Markov chain models have been used in advanced baseball analysis since 1960, although their use is still rare.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p02] Each half-inning of a baseball game fits the Markov chain state when the number of runners and outs are considered.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p02] During any at-bat, there are 24 possible combinations of number of outs and position of the runners.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p02] Mark Pankin shows that Markov chain models can be used to evaluate runs created for both individual players as well as a team.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p02] He also discusses various kinds of strategies and play conditions: how Markov chain models have been used to analyze statistics for game situations such as bunting and base stealing and differences when playing on grass vs.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p02] Markov processes can also be used to generate superficially real-looking text given a sample document.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p02] Markov processes are used in a variety of recreational "parody generator" software (see dissociated press, Jeff Harrison, Mark V.
[src:random-walk-theory/markov-chain-p02] Several open-source text generation libraries using Markov chains exist.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] In mathematics, a **random walk** is a stochastic process that describes a path that consists of a succession of random steps on some mathematical space.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] An elementary example of a random walk is one on the integer number line $\mathbb {Z}$ which starts at 0, and at each step moves +1 or −1 with equal probability.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] Other examples include the path traced by a molecule as it travels in a liquid or a gas (see Brownian motion), the search path of a foraging animal, or the price of a fluctuating stock and the financial status of a gambler.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] Random walks have applications to engineering and many scientific fields including ecology, psychology, computer science, physics, chemistry, biology, economics, and sociology.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] The term *random walk* was first introduced by Karl Pearson in 1905.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] Realizations of random walks can be obtained by Monte Carlo simulation.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] In certain contexts random walk is sometimes known as a **drunkard's walk**.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] A popular random walk model is that of a random walk on a regular lattice, where at each step the location jumps to another site according to some probability distribution.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] In a *simple random walk*, the location can only jump to neighboring sites of the lattice, forming a lattice path.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] In a *simple symmetric random walk* on a locally finite lattice, the probabilities of the location jumping to each one of its immediate neighbors are the same.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] The best-studied example is the random walk on the *d*-dimensional integer lattice (sometimes called the hypercubic lattice) $\mathbb {Z} ^{d}$ .
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] If, in addition, the state space is finite, the random walk model is called a *simple bordered symmetric random walk*, and the transition probabilities depend on the location of the state because on margin and corner states the movement is limited.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] An elementary example of a random walk is the random walk on the integer number line, $\mathbb {Z}$ , which starts at 0 and at each step moves +1 or −1 with equal probability.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] This walk can be illustrated as follows.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] A marker is placed at zero on the number line, and a fair coin is flipped.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] If it lands on heads, the marker is moved one unit to the right.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] If it lands on tails, the marker is moved one unit to the left.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] After five flips, the marker could now be on -5, -3, -1, 1, 3, 5.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] With five flips, three heads and two tails, in any order, it will land on 1.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] See the figure below for an illustration of the possible outcomes of 5 flips.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] This series (the sum of the sequence of −1s and 1s) gives the net distance walked, if each part of the walk is of length one.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] That is, the mean of all coin flips approaches zero as the number of flips increases.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] This hints that $E(|S_{n}|)\,\!$ , the expected translation distance after *n* steps, should be of the order of ${\sqrt {n}}$ .
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] To answer the question of how many times will a random walk cross a boundary line if permitted to continue walking forever, a simple random walk on $\mathbb {Z}$ will cross every point an infinite number of times.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] This result has many names: the *level-crossing phenomenon*, *recurrence* or the *gambler's ruin*.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] The reason for the last name is as follows: a gambler with a finite amount of money will eventually lose when playing *a fair game* against a bank with an infinite amount of money.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] The gambler's money will perform a random walk, and it will reach zero at some point, and the game will be over.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] If *a* and *b* are positive integers, then the expected number of steps until a one-dimensional simple random walk starting at 0 first hits *b* or −*a* is *ab*.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] The probability that this walk will hit *b* before −*a* is $a/(a+b)$ , which can be derived from the fact that simple random walk is a martingale.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] And these expectations and hitting probabilities can be computed in $O(a+b)$ in the general one-dimensional random walk Markov chain.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] Some of the results mentioned above can be derived from properties of Pascal's triangle.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] The number of different walks of *n* steps where each step is +1 or −1 is 2*n*.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] For the simple random walk, each of these walks is equally likely.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] In order for *Sn* to be equal to a number *k* it is necessary and sufficient that the number of +1 in the walk exceeds those of −1 by *k*.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] It follows +1 must appear (*n* + *k*)/2 times among *n* steps of a walk, hence the number of walks which satisfy $S_{n}=k$ equals the number of ways of choosing (*n* + *k*)/2 elements from an *n* element set, denoted ${\textstyle n \choose (n+k)/2}$ .
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] For this to have meaning, it is necessary that *n* + *k* be an even number, which implies *n* and *k* are either both even or both odd.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] Therefore, the probability that $S_{n}=k$ is equal to ${\textstyle 2^{-n}{n \choose (n+k)/2}}$ .
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] By representing entries of Pascal's triangle in terms of factorials and using Stirling's formula, one can obtain good estimates for these probabilities for large values of n .
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] This relation with Pascal's triangle is demonstrated for small values of *n*.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] At zero turns, the only possibility will be to remain at zero.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] However, at one turn, there is one chance of landing on −1 or one chance of landing on 1.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] At two turns, a marker at 1 could move to 2 or back to zero.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] A marker at −1, could move to −2 or back to zero.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] Therefore, there is one chance of landing on −2, two chances of landing on zero, and one chance of landing on 2.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] The central limit theorem and the law of the iterated logarithm describe important aspects of the behavior of simple random walks on $\mathbb {Z}$ .
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] In particular, the former entails that as *n* increases, the probabilities (proportional to the numbers in each row) approach a normal distribution.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] taking the limit (and observing that ${\textstyle {1}/{\sqrt {n}}}$ corresponds to the spacing of the scaling grid) one finds the gaussian density ${\textstyle f(x)={\frac {1}{2{\sqrt {\pi }}}}e^{-{x^{2}}}}$ .
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] Indeed, for a absolutely continuous random variable ${\textstyle X}$ with density ${\textstyle f_{X}}$ it holds ${\textstyle \mathbb {P} \left(X\in [x,x+dx)\right)=f_{X}(x)dx}$ , with ${\textstyle dx}$ corresponding to an infinitesimal spacing.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] As a direct generalization, one can consider random walks on crystal lattices (infinite-fold abelian covering graphs over finite graphs).
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] Actually it is possible to establish the central limit theorem and large deviation theorem in this setting.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] The heterogeneous random walk draws in each time step a random number that determines the local jumping probabilities and then a random number that determines the actual jump direction.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] The main question is the probability of staying in each of the various sites after t jumps, and in the limit of this probability when t is very large.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] In higher dimensions, the set of randomly walked points has interesting geometric properties.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] In fact, one gets a discrete fractal, that is, a set which exhibits stochastic self-similarity on large scales.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] On small scales, one can observe "jaggedness" resulting from the grid on which the walk is performed.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] The trajectory of a random walk is the collection of points visited, considered as a set with disregard to *when* the walk arrived at the point.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] In one dimension, the trajectory is simply all points between the minimum height and the maximum height the walk achieved (both are, on average, on the order of ${\sqrt {n}}$ ).
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] To visualize the two-dimensional case, one can imagine a person walking randomly around a city.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] The city is effectively infinite and arranged in a square grid of sidewalks.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] At every intersection, the person randomly chooses one of the four possible routes (including the one originally travelled from).
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] Formally, this is a random walk on the set of all points in the plane with integer coordinates.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] To answer the question of the person ever getting back to the original starting point of the walk, this is the 2-dimensional equivalent of the level-crossing problem discussed above.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] In 1921 George Pólya proved that the person almost surely would in a 2-dimensional random walk, but for 3 dimensions or higher, the probability of returning to the origin decreases as the number of dimensions increases.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] In 3 dimensions, the probability decreases to roughly 34%.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] The mathematician Shizuo Kakutani was known to refer to this result with the following quote: "A drunk man will find his way home, but a drunk bird may get lost forever".
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] Paul Erdős and Samuel James Taylor also showed in 1960 that for dimensions less or equal than 4, two independent random walks starting from any two given points have infinitely many intersections almost surely, but for dimensions higher than 5, they almost surely intersect only finitely often.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] The asymptotic function for a two-dimensional random walk as the number of steps increases is given by a Rayleigh distribution.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] The probability distribution is a function of the radius from the origin and the step length is constant for each step.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] Here, the step length is assumed to be 1, N is the total number of steps and r is the radius from the origin.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] A Wiener process is a stochastic process with similar behavior to Brownian motion, the physical phenomenon of a minute particle diffusing in a fluid.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] A Wiener process is the scaling limit of random walk in dimension 1.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] This means that if there is a random walk with very small steps, there is an approximation to a Wiener process (and, less accurately, to Brownian motion).
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] To be more precise, if the step size is ε, one needs to take a walk of length *L*/ε2 to approximate a Wiener length of *L*.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] As the step size tends to 0 (and the number of steps increases proportionally), random walk converges to a Wiener process in an appropriate sense.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] Formally, if *B* is the space of all paths of length *L* with the maximum topology, and if *M* is the space of measure over *B* with the norm topology, then the convergence is in the space *M*.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] Similarly, a Wiener process in several dimensions is the scaling limit of random walk in the same number of dimensions.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] A random walk is a discrete fractal (a function with integer dimensions; 1, 2, ...), but a Wiener process trajectory is a true fractal, and there is a connection between the two.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] For example, take a random walk until it hits a circle of radius *r* times the step length.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] The average number of steps it performs is *r*2.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] This fact is the *discrete version* of the fact that a Wiener process walk is a fractal of Hausdorff dimension 2.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] In two dimensions, the average number of points the same random walk has on the *boundary* of its trajectory is *r*4/3.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] This corresponds to the fact that the boundary of the trajectory of a Wiener process is a fractal of dimension 4/3, a fact predicted by Mandelbrot using simulations but proved only in 2000 by Lawler, Schramm and Werner.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] A Wiener process enjoys many symmetries a random walk does not.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] For example, a Wiener process walk is invariant to rotations, but the random walk is not, since the underlying grid is not (random walk is invariant to rotations by 90 degrees, but Wiener processes are invariant to rotations by, for example, 17 degrees too).
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] This means that in many cases, problems on a random walk are easier to solve by translating them to a Wiener process, solving the problem there, and then translating back.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] On the other hand, some problems are easier to solve with random walks due to its discrete nature.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] Random walk and Wiener process can be *coupled*, namely manifested on the same probability space in a dependent way that forces them to be quite close.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] The simplest such coupling is the Skorokhod embedding, but there exist more precise couplings, such as Komlós–Major–Tusnády approximation theorem.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] The convergence of a random walk toward the Wiener process is controlled by the central limit theorem, and by Donsker's theorem.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] where *t* is the time elapsed since the start of the random walk, $\varepsilon$ is the size of a step of the random walk, and $\delta t$ is the time elapsed between two successive steps.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] This corresponds to the Green's function of the diffusion equation that controls the Wiener process, which suggests that, after a large number of steps, the random walk converges toward a Wiener process.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] The two expressions of the variance above correspond to the distribution associated to the vector ${\vec {R}}$ that links the two ends of the random walk, in 3D.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] The variance associated to each component $R_{x}$ , $R_{y}$ or $R_{z}$ is only one third of this value (still in 3D).
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] A random walk having a step size that varies according to a normal distribution ${\mathcal {N}}(\mu ,\sigma ^{2})$ , $\mu$ being the mean and $\sigma$ being the standard deviation, is used as a model for real-world time-series data such as financial markets.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] Here, the step size is given by the inverse cumulative normal distribution $\Phi ^{-1}(x,\mu ,\sigma ),$ where $x\in \{0,1\}$ is a uniformly distributed random number.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] If $\mu$ is nonzero, the random walk will vary about a linear trend.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] If $v_{s}$ is the starting value of the random walk, the expected value after n steps will be $v_{s}+n\mu$ .
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] But for the Gaussian random walk, this is just the standard deviation of the translation distance's distribution after n steps.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] Hence, if $\mu =0$ , and since the root mean square (RMS) translation distance is one standard deviation, there is a 68.27% probability that the RMS translation distance after n steps will fall between $\pm \sigma {\sqrt {n}}$ .
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] The number of distinct sites visited by a single random walker $S(t)$ has been studied extensively for square and cubic lattices and for fractals.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] This quantity is useful for the analysis of problems of trapping and kinetic reactions.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] It is also related to the vibrational density of states, diffusion reactions processes and spread of populations in ecology.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] Therefore, it is impossible to encode ${\{Z_{n}\}_{n=1}^{N}}$ using a binary code of less than $NR(D_{\theta })$ bits and recover it with expected mean squared error less than $D_{\theta }$ .
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] In financial economics, the random walk hypothesis is used to model share prices and other factors.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] Empirical studies found some deviations from this theoretical model, especially in short term and long term correlations.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] In semiconductor manufacturing, random walks are used to analyze the effects of thermal treatment at smaller nodes.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] It is applied to understand the diffusion of dopants, defects and other impurities during the critical fabrication steps.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] Random walk treatments are also used to study the diffusion of reactants, products and plasma during chemical vapor deposition processes.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] Continuum diffusion has been used to study the flow of gases, at macroscopic scales, in CVD reactors.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] However, smaller dimensions and increased complexity has forced us to treat them with random walk.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] This allows for accurate analysis of stochastic processes, at molecular level and smaller, in semiconductor manufacturing.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] In computer science, random walks have been used to estimate the size of the Web.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] In computer programming it is possible to calculate pi with a random walk.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] Random walks have been used in network analysis to calculate the probability two unlinked nodes will be linked in the future based on the current state of the network.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] Various algorithms are discussed in including PageRank and supervised random walks.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] In image segmentation, random walks are used to determine the labels (i.e., "object" or "background") to associate with each pixel.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] This algorithm is typically referred to as the random walker segmentation algorithm.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] The Twitter website used random walks to make suggestions of whom to follow.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] As mentioned, the range of natural phenomena which have been subject to attempts at description by some flavour of random walks is considerable.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] This is particularly the case in the fields of physics, chemistry, materials science, and biology.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] A number of types of stochastic processes have been considered that are similar to the pure random walks but where the simple structure is allowed to be more generalized.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] The *pure* structure can be characterized by the steps being defined by independent and identically distributed random variables.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] Random walks can take place on a variety of spaces, such as graphs, the integers, the real line, the plane or higher-dimensional vector spaces, on curved surfaces or higher-dimensional Riemannian manifolds, and on groups.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] It is also possible to define random walks which take their steps at random times, and in that case, the position X t has to be defined for all times *t* ∈ [0, +∞).
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] Specific cases or limits of random walks include the Lévy flight and diffusion models such as Brownian motion.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] A random walk of length *k* on a possibly infinite graph *G* with a root *0* is a stochastic process with random variables $X_{1},X_{2},\dots ,X_{k}$ such that $X_{1}=0$ and ${X_{i+1}}$ is a vertex chosen uniformly at random from the neighbors of $X_{i}$ .
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] Then the number $p_{v,w,k}(G)$ is the probability that a random walk of length *k* starting at *v* ends at *w*.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] In particular, if *G* is a graph with root *0*, $p_{0,0,2k}$ is the probability that a $2k$ -step random walk returns to *0*.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] Building on the analogy from the earlier section on higher dimensions, assume now that our city is no longer a perfect square grid.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] When our person reaches a certain junction, he picks between the variously available roads with equal probability.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] Thus, if the junction has seven exits the person will go to each one with probability one-seventh.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] It turns out that under rather mild conditions, the answer is still yes, but depending on the graph, the answer to the variant question 'Will two persons meet again?' may not be that they meet infinitely often almost surely.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] An example of a case where the person will reach his home almost surely is when the lengths of all the blocks are between *a* and *b* (where *a* and *b* are any two finite positive numbers).
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] Notice that we do not assume that the graph is planar, i.e. the city may contain tunnels and bridges.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] One way to prove this result is using the connection to electrical networks.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] Take a map of the city and place a one ohm resistor on every block.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] Now measure the "resistance between a point and infinity".
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] In other words, choose some number *R* and take all the points in the electrical network with distance bigger than *R* from our point and wire them together.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] This is now a finite electrical network, and we may measure the resistance from our point to the wired points.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] The limit is called the *resistance between a point and infinity*.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] In other words, in a transient system, one only needs to overcome a finite resistance to get to infinity from any point.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] In a recurrent system, the resistance from any point to infinity is infinite.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] This characterization of transience and recurrence is very useful, and specifically it allows us to analyze the case of a city drawn in the plane with the distances bounded.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] A random walk on a graph is a very special case of a Markov chain.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] Unlike a general Markov chain, random walk on a graph enjoys a property called *time symmetry* or *reversibility*.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] Roughly speaking, this property, also called the principle of detailed balance, means that the probabilities to traverse a given path in one direction or the other have a very simple connection between them (if the graph is regular, they are just equal).
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] This property has important consequences.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] Starting in the 1980s, much research has gone into connecting properties of the graph to random walks.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] In addition to the electrical network connection described above, there are important connections to isoperimetric inequalities, see more here, functional inequalities such as Sobolev and Poincaré inequalities and properties of solutions of Laplace's equation.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] A significant portion of this research was focused on Cayley graphs of finitely generated groups.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] In many cases these discrete results carry over to, or are derived from manifolds and Lie groups.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] In the context of random graphs, particularly that of the Erdős–Rényi model, analytical results to some properties of random walkers have been obtained.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] A good reference for random walk on graphs is the online book by Aldous and Fill.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] If the transition kernel $p(x,y)$ is itself random (based on an environment $\omega$ ) then the random walk is called a "random walk in random environment".
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] When the law of the random walk includes the randomness of $\omega$ , the law is called the annealed law; on the other hand, if $\omega$ is seen as fixed, the law is called a quenched law.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] See the book of Hughes, the book of Revesz, or the lecture notes of Zeitouni.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] We can think about choosing every possible edge with the same probability as maximizing uncertainty (entropy) locally.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] We could also do it globally – in maximal entropy random walk (MERW) we want all paths to be equally probable, or in other words: for every two vertexes, each path of given length is equally probable.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] This random walk has much stronger localization properties.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] There are a number of interesting models of random paths in which each step depends on the past in a complicated manner.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] All are more complex for solving analytically than the usual random walk; still, the behavior of any model of a random walker is obtainable using computers.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] The self-avoiding walk of length *n* on $\mathbb {Z} ^{d}$ is the random *n*-step path which starts at the origin, makes transitions only between adjacent sites in $\mathbb {Z} ^{d}$ , never revisit a site, and is chosen uniformly among all such paths.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] In two dimensions, due to self-trapping, a typical self-avoiding walk is very short, while in higher dimension it grows beyond all bounds.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] This model has often been used in polymer physics (since the 1960s).
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] Random walk chosen to maximize entropy rate, has much stronger localization properties.
[src:random-walk-theory/random-walk] Random walks where the direction of movement at one time is correlated with the direction of movement at the next time.
[src:random-walk-theory/self-avoiding-walk] Is there a formula or algorithm that can calculate the number of self-avoiding walks in any given lattice?
[src:random-walk-theory/self-avoiding-walk] In mathematics, a **self-avoiding walk** (**SAW**) is a sequence of moves on a lattice (a lattice path) that does not visit the same point more than once.
[src:random-walk-theory/self-avoiding-walk] This is a special case of the graph theoretical notion of a path.
[src:random-walk-theory/self-avoiding-walk] A **self-avoiding polygon** (**SAP**) is a closed self-avoiding walk on a lattice.
[src:random-walk-theory/self-avoiding-walk] Very little is known rigorously about the self-avoiding walk from a mathematical perspective, although physicists have provided numerous conjectures that are believed to be true and are strongly supported by numerical simulations.
[src:random-walk-theory/self-avoiding-walk] In computational physics, a self-avoiding walk is a chain-like path in **R**2 or **R**3 with a certain number of nodes, typically a fixed step length and has the property that it doesn't cross itself or another walk.
[src:random-walk-theory/self-avoiding-walk] A system of SAWs satisfies the so-called excluded volume condition.
[src:random-walk-theory/self-avoiding-walk] In higher dimensions, the SAW is believed to behave much like the ordinary random walk.
[src:random-walk-theory/self-avoiding-walk] SAWs and SAPs play a central role in the modeling of the topological and knot-theoretic behavior of thread- and loop-like molecules such as proteins.
[src:random-walk-theory/self-avoiding-walk] Indeed, SAWs may have first been introduced by the chemist Paul Flory in order to model the real-life behavior of chain-like entities such as solvents and polymers, whose physical volume prohibits multiple occupation of the same spatial point.
[src:random-walk-theory/self-avoiding-walk] For example, in *d* = 2 the fractal dimension is 4/3, for *d* = 3 it is close to 5/3 while for *d* ≥ 4 the fractal dimension is 2.
[src:random-walk-theory/self-avoiding-walk] The dimension is called the upper critical dimension above which excluded volume is negligible.
[src:random-walk-theory/self-avoiding-walk] A SAW that does not satisfy the excluded volume condition was recently studied to model explicit surface geometry resulting from expansion of a SAW.
[src:random-walk-theory/self-avoiding-walk] The average size of a self-avoiding walk increases with respect to its length according to an exponent that is the reciprocal of the fractal dimension.
[src:random-walk-theory/self-avoiding-walk] The radius of gyration of a SAW depends on the 3/4 power of length in two dimensions, and approximately the 3/5th power in three dimensions.
[src:random-walk-theory/self-avoiding-walk] The properties of SAWs cannot be calculated analytically, so numerical simulations are employed.
[src:random-walk-theory/self-avoiding-walk] The pivot algorithm is a common method for Markov chain Monte Carlo simulations for the uniform measure on n-step self-avoiding walks.
[src:random-walk-theory/self-avoiding-walk] The pivot algorithm works by taking a self-avoiding walk and randomly choosing a point on this walk, and then applying symmetrical transformations (rotations and reflections) on the walk after the nth step to create a new walk.
[src:random-walk-theory/self-avoiding-walk] Calculating the number of self-avoiding walks in any given lattice is a common computational problem.
[src:random-walk-theory/self-avoiding-walk] There is currently no known formula, although there are rigorous methods of approximation.
[src:random-walk-theory/self-avoiding-walk] One of the phenomena associated with self-avoiding walks and statistical physics models in general is the notion of universality, that is, independence of macroscopic observables from microscopic details, such as the choice of the lattice.
[src:random-walk-theory/self-avoiding-walk] One important quantity that appears in conjectures for universal laws is the connective constant, defined as follows.
[src:random-walk-theory/self-avoiding-walk] Let cn denote the number of n-step self-avoiding walks.
[src:random-walk-theory/self-avoiding-walk] Since every (*n* + *m*)-step self avoiding walk can be decomposed into an n-step self-avoiding walk and an m-step self-avoiding walk, it follows that *c**n*+*m* ≤ *cncm*.
[src:random-walk-theory/self-avoiding-walk] μ is called the **connective constant**, since cn depends on the particular lattice chosen for the walk so does μ.
[src:random-walk-theory/self-avoiding-walk] For other lattices, μ has only been approximated numerically, and is believed not to even be an algebraic number.
[src:random-walk-theory/self-avoiding-walk] as *n* → ∞, where μ depends on the lattice, but the power law correction $n^{\frac {11}{32}}$ does not; in other words, this law is believed to be universal.
[src:random-walk-theory/self-avoiding-walk] The growing self-avoiding walk (GSAW) is a dynamical process in which a walk starts at the origin of a lattice and takes a step to an unoccupied site in a random direction.
[src:random-walk-theory/self-avoiding-walk] When there are no empty adjacent sites, the walk is said to be trapped, similar to the ending scenario in the video game Snake.
[src:random-walk-theory/self-avoiding-walk] On a square lattice it is known from computer simulations that the average number of steps reached by a growing self-avoiding walk is approximately 71.
[src:random-walk-theory/self-avoiding-walk] The shortest walk that leads to trapping on a square lattice is six steps, and can be achieved by starting on an empty lattice and moving up, right, right, down, down, left, and up.
[src:random-walk-theory/self-avoiding-walk] The average number of steps to trapping depends on the lattice or network, it is similar for the honeycomb lattice but near 78 for the triangular lattice.
[src:random-walk-theory/self-avoiding-walk] The average trapping length is much higher in three dimensions, being close to 4000 for the simple cubic lattice.
[src:random-walk-theory/self-avoiding-walk] The statistics of the traditional self-avoiding walk assume that each walk of a given length is equally likely, which is not the case for GSAWs.
[src:random-walk-theory/self-avoiding-walk] For example, there are 100 square lattice SAWs of length 4 starting at the origin, and four that are completely straight, such that there is a 0.04 probability of such a SAW being straight.
[src:random-walk-theory/self-avoiding-walk] However, a GSAW must make its first step in any direction with probability 1, its second in the same direction with probability 1/3, as with its third and fourth steps.
[src:random-walk-theory/self-avoiding-walk] Thus the probability of a GSAW being straight is 1/81≈0.012.
[src:random-walk-theory/self-avoiding-walk] For this reason, GSAWs are empirically observed in simulations to have a smaller scaling exponent (the relationship between the average radius of gyration and length) than the 3/4 predicted by the Flory model, and is observed to be close to 0.68.
[src:random-walk-theory/self-avoiding-walk] Self-avoiding polygons in three dimensions may form knots.
[src:random-walk-theory/self-avoiding-walk] On a simple cubic lattice the shortest knotted self-avoiding polygon is a trefoil knot that occupies 24 vertices.
[src:random-walk-theory/self-avoiding-walk] As self-avoiding polygons of greater length are considered, the probability of finding knots increases.
[src:random-walk-theory/self-avoiding-walk] It is proven that as the length of a randomly chosen SAP increases, the probability of finding an unknot decreases exponentially, implying that the probability of a self-avoiding polygon being knotted approaches 100% as its length increases.
[src:random-walk-theory/self-avoiding-walk] The length of a SAP at which the probability of knotting on a face-centered cubic lattice reaches 50% is approximately 100,000, and this may vary in other lattices.
[src:random-walk-theory/self-avoiding-walk] Self-avoiding walks that are not closed into polygons may also form entanglements that are colloquially recognized as knots, but these are not formally considered knots within knot theory unless the two ends of the walk are connected in some way.
[src:random-walk-theory/self-avoiding-walk] Self-avoiding walks have also been studied in the context of network theory.
[src:random-walk-theory/self-avoiding-walk] In this context, it is customary to treat the SAW as a dynamical process, such that in every time-step a walker randomly hops between neighboring nodes of the network.
[src:random-walk-theory/self-avoiding-walk] The walk ends when the walker reaches a dead-end state, such that it can no longer progress to newly un-visited nodes.
[src:random-walk-theory/self-avoiding-walk] It was recently found that on Erdős–Rényi networks, the distribution of path lengths of such dynamically grown SAWs can be calculated analytically, and follows the Gompertz distribution.
[src:random-walk-theory/self-avoiding-walk] For arbitrary networks, the distribution of path lengths of the walk, the degree distribution of the non-visited network and the first-hitting-time distribution to a node can be obtained by solving a set of coupled recurrence equations.
[src:random-walk-theory/self-avoiding-walk] Consider the uniform measure on n-step self-avoiding walks in the full plane.
[src:random-walk-theory/self-avoiding-walk] It is currently unknown whether the limit of the uniform measure as *n* → ∞ induces a measure on infinite full-plane walks.
[src:random-walk-theory/self-avoiding-walk] However, Harry Kesten has shown that such a measure exists for self-avoiding walks in the half-plane.
[src:random-walk-theory/self-avoiding-walk] One important question involving self-avoiding walks is the existence and conformal invariance of the scaling limit, that is, the limit as the length of the walk goes to infinity and the mesh of the lattice goes to zero.
[src:random-walk-theory/self-avoiding-walk] The scaling limit of the self-avoiding walk is conjectured to be described by Schramm–Loewner evolution with parameter *κ* = ⁠8/3⁠.
